                <fr:title text="Extreme value theorem">Extreme value theorem</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>theorem</fr:taxon>
                <fr:meta name="source"><fr:link href="/lankham-2016-linear/" title="Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics" uri="http://localhost:8000/lankham-2016-linear/" display-uri="lankham-2016-linear" type="local">Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics</fr:link> Theorem 3.1.2</fr:meta>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  D\to \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> be a continuous function on the closed disc <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D_{R}=\{(x_{1},x_{2})\in \mathbb {R}^{2}\mid  x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}\leq  R^{2}\}]]></fr:tex> of radius <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is bounded and attains its minimum and maximum values on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>. In other words, there exists points <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{\text {min}},x_{\text {max}}\in  D]]></fr:tex> such that for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  D]]></fr:tex> we have
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[f(x_{\text {min}})\leq  f(x)\leq  f(x_{\text {max}})]]></fr:tex></html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
