                <fr:title text="Fundamental Theorem of Algebra">Fundamental Theorem of Algebra</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>theorem</fr:taxon>
                <fr:meta name="source"><fr:link href="/lankham-2016-linear/" title="Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics" uri="http://localhost:8000/lankham-2016-linear/" display-uri="lankham-2016-linear" type="local">Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics</fr:link> Lemma 3.1.1</fr:meta>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> be a positive integer, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{0},…,a_{n}\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> be complex numbers with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{n}\neq 0]]></fr:tex>. Then the polynomial equation
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[a_{n}z^{n}+…+a_{1}z+a_{0}=0]]></fr:tex>
has at least one solution in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
                <html:p>(It seems like every field has its own proof of the fundamental theorem of algebra, so I will link them here:)</html:p>
                <html:ul>
                  <html:li>Proof: <fr:link href="/complex-000K/" title="Fundamental Theorem of Algebra via Extreme Value Theorem" uri="http://localhost:8000/complex-000K/" display-uri="complex-000K" type="local">Fundamental Theorem of Algebra via Extreme Value Theorem</fr:link></html:li>
                </html:ul>
