                <fr:title text="Properties of degrees of polynomials under arithmetic">Properties of degrees of polynomials under arithmetic</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>theorem</fr:taxon>
                <fr:meta name="source"><fr:link href="/lankham-2016-linear/" title="Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics" uri="http://localhost:8000/lankham-2016-linear/" display-uri="lankham-2016-linear" type="local">Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics</fr:link> Lemma 3.2.1</fr:meta>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p(z)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q(z)]]></fr:tex> be nonzero polynomials. Then:</html:p>
                <html:ol><html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\deg (p(z)\pm  q(z))\leq \max (\deg (p(z)),\deg (q(z)))]]></fr:tex>, and</html:li>
<html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\deg (p(z)q(z))=\deg (p(z))+\deg (q(z))]]></fr:tex></html:li></html:ol>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>12</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>9</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>http://localhost:8000/complex-000N/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>complex-000N</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/complex-000N/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="" />
                <fr:taxon>theorem</fr:taxon>
                <fr:meta name="source"><fr:link href="/lankham-2016-linear/" title="Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics" uri="http://localhost:8000/lankham-2016-linear/" display-uri="lankham-2016-linear" type="local">Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics</fr:link> Lemma 3.2.2</fr:meta>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> be a positive integer, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{0},…,a_{n}\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{n}\neq 0]]></fr:tex>. We define the function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon \mathbb {C}\to \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> by
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[f(z)=a_{n}z^{n}+…+a_{1}z+a_{0}]]></fr:tex>
Then the following all hold:</html:p>
                <html:ol><html:li>For any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(w)=0]]></fr:tex> if there exists a polynomial <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g\colon \mathbb {C}\to \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> of degree <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\deg (g)=n-1]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(z)=(z-w)g(z)]]></fr:tex>;</html:li>
<html:li>There are at most <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> distinct complex numbers <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> for which <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(w)=0]]></fr:tex>; i.e., <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> has at most <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> distinct roots;</html:li>
<html:li>(Fundamental theorem of algebra, 2.0) There exists <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n+1]]></fr:tex> complex numbers <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w_{0},…,w_{n}\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> (not necessarily distinct) such that
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[f(z)=w_{0}(z-w_{1})(z-w_{2})(…)(z-w_{n})]]></fr:tex>
In other words, every polynomial function with coefficients over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> can be factored into linear factors over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex></html:li></html:ol>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
