            <fr:title text="Adjoining a root to rationals is a field extension">Adjoining a root to rationals is a field extension</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>example</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>We can adjoin <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {i}=\sqrt {-1}]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex> to obtain the <fr:link href="/nt-000F/" title="Field extension" uri="http://localhost:8000/nt-000F/" display-uri="nt-000F" type="local">Field extension</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}(\mathrm {i})]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
            <html:p>More generally, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p(x)\in \mathbb {Q}[x]]]></fr:tex> is a nonconstant polynomial, then we see <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p(x)\in \mathbb {C}[x]]]></fr:tex> and so by the <fr:link href="/complex-000J/" title="Fundamental Theorem of Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/complex-000J/" display-uri="complex-000J" type="local">Fundamental Theorem of Algebra</fr:link> there is a root <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[c\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p(c)=0]]></fr:tex>. We can adjoin <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[c]]></fr:tex> to the rationals to get a field extension <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}(c) / \mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
