            <fr:title text="Fundamental Theorem of Algebra via Extreme Value Theorem">Fundamental Theorem of Algebra via Extreme Value Theorem</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>proof</fr:taxon>
            <fr:meta name="source"><fr:link href="/lankham-2016-linear/" title="Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics" uri="http://localhost:8000/lankham-2016-linear/" display-uri="lankham-2016-linear" type="local">Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics</fr:link> Lemma 3.1</fr:meta>
            <fr:meta name="source"><fr:link href="/axler-1996-linear/" title="Linear Algebra Done Right" uri="http://localhost:8000/axler-1996-linear/" display-uri="axler-1996-linear" type="local">Linear Algebra Done Right</fr:link> Theorem 4.12</fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>By <fr:link href="/complex-000I/" title="Modulus of complex polynomial attains a minimum value" uri="http://localhost:8000/complex-000I/" display-uri="complex-000I" type="local">Modulus of complex polynomial attains a minimum value</fr:link>, we see that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|f|]]></fr:tex> attains its minimum value. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z_{0}\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> be a point where the minimum is attained. We will show if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(z_{0})\neq 0]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z_{0}]]></fr:tex> is not a minimum (which proves by contrapositive that the minimum of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|f(z)|]]></fr:tex> is zero, and therefore <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(z_{0})=0]]></fr:tex>).</html:p>
            <html:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(z_{0})\neq 0]]></fr:tex>, then we can define a new function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g\colon \mathbb {C}\to \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> by
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[g(z) = \frac {f(z+z_{0})}{f(z_{0})}]]></fr:tex>
This is a polynomial of degree <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n=\deg (f)]]></fr:tex>. We claim <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|f|]]></fr:tex> attains a minimum at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z_{0}]]></fr:tex> if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|g|]]></fr:tex> attains a minimum value at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z=0]]></fr:tex>. Moreover, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g(0)=1]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
            <html:p>We can write
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[g(z)=1+a_{k}z^{k}+…+a_{n}z^{n}]]></fr:tex>
where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex> is the smallest positive integer such that the coefficient of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z^{k}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g]]></fr:tex> is nonzero, i.e., <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{k}\neq 0]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
            <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> be such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b^{k}=-1/a_{k}]]></fr:tex>. There exists a constant <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[c>1]]></fr:tex> such that if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[0<t<1]]></fr:tex>, then
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[|g(tb)|\leq |1+a_{k}t^{k}b^{k}|+t^{k+1}c=1-t^{k}(1-tc)]]></fr:tex>
Taking <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[t=1/(2c)]]></fr:tex> in this inequality, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|g(tb)|<1]]></fr:tex>. But this contradicts the assumption that the minimum of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|g(z)|]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|g(0)|=1]]></fr:tex>. This contradiction implies the result.</html:p>
